        "setup": "Create a customer session from your backend with the [Create Customer Session](https://polar.sh/docs/api-reference/customer-portal/sessions/create) API using an Organization Access Token. The response includes a `token` value that authenticates Customer Portal API calls as that customer. Use it as `Authorization: Bearer <token>`.",
        "acquisition": "manual"
      },
      "polar_oauth_client": {
        "type": "oauth2",
        "label": "OAuth 2.0 client (Client ID and Client Secret)",
        "generateUrl": "https://polar.sh/settings#oauth",
        "setup": "Open your [User Settings](https://polar.sh/settings#oauth) and create an OAuth 2.0 client. Configure the application name, client type, redirect URIs, scopes, and homepage URL. After creation, Polar issues a `client_id` and `client_secret`. For public clients configured as such, the token endpoint can be used without `client_secret`, but PKCE is required. Discovery metadata is published at [OpenID Configuration](https://api.polar.sh/.well-known/openid-configuration).",
        "acquisition": "manual"
      },
      "polar_oauth_access_token": {
        "type": "bearer",
        "label": "OAuth 2.0 access token",
        "generateUrl": "https://polar.sh/docs/integrate/oauth2/connect",
        "setup": "First create an [OAuth 2.0 client](https://polar.sh/docs/integrate/oauth2/setup). Then send users through the [OAuth 2.0 Connect](https://polar.sh/docs/integrate/oauth2/connect) authorization code flow using `https://polar.sh/oauth2/authorize`, and exchange the returned code at `https://api.polar.sh/v1/oauth2/token`. Polar returns an `access_token` (and usually a `refresh_token`). Use the access token as `Authorization: Bearer <token>`.",
        "acquisition": "manual"
      }
